Here’s what caught our attention on Tuesday: 1. AngloGold Ashanti results For the year ended December 31 2018, mining company AngloGold Ashanti is reporting an increase in headline earnings per share to 53 cents, up from 6 cents in 2017. The company’s adjusted earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortisation amounted to $1.48 billion, while free cash flow improved to $67 million from $1 million in 2017. The company is declaring a dividend of 95 SA cents per share for the period. AngloGold also highlighted the completion of its restructuring, strong operational performance, which are now cash-free flow positive. 2. Murray & Roberts trading update Construction firm, Murray & Roberts which has been facing a number of challenges in recent times from German firm Aton, is flagging an improvement in earnings per share and headline earnings per share for the six months ended December 31 2018. The company expects basic earnings per share to increase between 57% and 75% to 44 and 49 cents, while expecting basic headline earnings per share to increase between 54% and 71% to 43 and 48 cents per share. The company is citing improvements to smaller losses in discontinued operations,but expects challenges in its oil and gas; and power and water operations to negatively affect its FY2019 performance. 3. BHP Group results Mining company, BHP is reporting a significant increase in headline earnings for the half year ended December 31 2018, as it rose up to US$ 4 353 million from US$ 2 166 million in 2017. The company’s headline earnings per share also increased to 82.1 US cents from 40.7 US cents in 2017. BHP attributes its increased cash returns to its focus on portfolio simplification, cash generation and capital generation during the period. An interim dividend of 55 US cents has been declared. 4. Bosasa goes bust The services company, formerly known as Bosasa, has come into the spotlight again, this time, for filing for liquidation. News emerged on Monday that banks are opting to close its accounts, citing ‘reputational risk’ after the company was at the centre of topic at state capture hearings two weeks ago. The company, which employs close to 4 500 employees, says its voluntary liquidation will not impact its operations. Read more here. <a href="http://iono.fm/e/656557">Content hosted by iono.fm</a> 5. Rand update and budget preview It’s a day before finance minister Tito Mboweni steps forward to deliver the 2019 budget. A number of issues are looming, including funding solutions for ailing SOEs Eskom and SAA, which are both planning a split; economic growth, debt numbers and possible changes to taxes. Traders are playing a cautious game. The rand on Tuesday was at R14.19 to the dollar at 9:54. Read: #Budget2019: 4 things to watch,